{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535043"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:52:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:52:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15242"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15242"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.46,0.27,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105630"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2779"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"5587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105630"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is reviewed on the medical ward due to low blood pressure. The review was requested after she got up to use the bathroom and felt dizzy. She was admitted three days ago with gastroenteritis. She has a past medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis, and biventricular heart failure. Her medications include amlodipine, paracetamol, metoprolol and furosemide. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. While lying flat, her pulse rate is 85/min and blood pressure 105/65 mmHg. On sitting up, her pulse rate increases to 110/min and blood pressure drops to 85/50 mmHg. Her respiratory rate is 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. Her mucous membranes are dry, and her jugular venous pressure is not able to be appreciated. Her chest reveals fine bibasal crepitations and she has pitting oedema to her ankles. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 3.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 12.0 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 145 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial fluid resuscitation strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1L crystalloid bolus over 15 minutes","250mL crystalloid bolus over 30 minutes","500mL colloid bolus over 30 minutes","Maintenance rate crystalloid infusion","2L crystalloid bolus over one hour"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex fluid management scenario in an elderly patient with both hypovolaemia and underlying cardiac dysfunction. The clinical findings suggest significant volume depletion (postural hypotension, tachycardia, dry mucous membranes), but the history of cardiac dysfunction with evidence of pulmonary and peripheral oedema warrant caution. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E250mL crystalloid bolus over 30 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E represents the most balanced approach. This rate allows for careful monitoring of the patient\u0027s response while addressing the immediate volume needs. The slower rate and smaller volume reduce the risk of fluid overload in a patient with compromised cardiac function. More intravenous therapy can always be administered if required after a fluid review following the initial bolus. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1L crystalloid bolus over 15 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E would be too aggressive given the patient\u0027s cardiac status and age. While this might be appropriate in a younger patient with normal cardiac function, it carries a significant risk of precipitating pulmonary oedema in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500mL colloid bolus over 30 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E would not offer any advantage over crystalloid in this situation and may be associated with increased risks. Current evidence does not support routine use of colloids over crystalloids for fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintenance rate crystalloid infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be too conservative given the significant postural changes and evidence of organ hypoperfusion (elevated urea:creatinine ratio). The patient requires more immediate volume replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2L crystalloid bolus over one hour\u003C/strong\u003E represents an excessive volume that could overwhelm the patient\u0027s cardiac reserve. The presence of bibasal crepitations already suggests some degree of fluid overload, making this option particularly risky.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising that while the patient needs fluid resuscitation, their cardiac status necessitates a more measured approach with frequent reassessment. After the initial bolus, the patient should be reassessed for signs of both improved perfusion and potential fluid overload before deciding on further fluid administration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Assessment of volume status through clinical examination and bedside tests is crucial in evaluating hypotension.","Postural hypotension with tachycardia suggests significant volume depletion.","Early fluid resuscitation is essential in managing hypovolaemic hypotension, but the rate and type must be carefully considered in elderly patients."],"references":["Wittczak A, \u015alot M, Bielecka-Dabrowa A. The importance of optimal hydration in patients with heart failure\u2014Not always too much fluid. Biomedicines. 2023;11(10):2684. doi:10.3390/biomedicines11102684. Available at: https://www.mdpi.com/2227-9059/11/10/2684","Castera MR, Borhade MB. Fluid Management. [Updated 2023 Oct 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532305/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15242"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T09:40:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T18:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7933"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105630"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type